Total CO2 Emissions data

total_Co2<-monthly_dta_ts$CO2_ElecPower[,"V10"]
autoplot(total_Co2,ylab="Metric Tons of CO2") +
    ggtitle("CO2 Emissions for Electric Power")

Look at small window of time to see seasonality

autoplot(cbind("CO2 Emission"  = window(total_Co2,start=2006,end=2008)),ylab="Emissions")

Has large peak in summer and a smaller peak in the winter (makes sense - AC and heat respectively)

Decomposition with multiplicative seasonality

total_Co2 %>% decompose(type="multiplicative") %>% autoplot + xlab("Year")

Fit Holt-Winter SES model with multiplicative seasonality (seasonality changes to a small degree - model fits better ). HW does not require stationarity so no need for transformations

fit_hw_mult<-hw(total_Co2,h=forecastlength,seasonal="multiplicative")
summary(fit_hw_mult$model)

model_func_hw <- function(x, h){hw(x,h=h,seasonal="multiplicative")}
error1hw <- tsCV(total_Co2, model_func_hw, h=12)
error2hw <- tsCV(total_Co2, model_func_hw, h=12, window = 48)
RMS1hw<-sqrt(mean(error1hw^2, na.rm=TRUE))
RMS2hw<-sqrt(mean(error2hw^2, na.rm=TRUE))

ARIMA/SARIMA models

ARIMA/SARIMA models require stationarity - investigate how time series gets to stationarity.

Break up time series into windows based on interventions/changes in trend

Work with last window (2008 and onwards) as this will be used in forecasting

CO2_Window<-window(total_Co2,start=2008)
autoplot(cbind("CO2 Emission"  = CO2_Window))

tsdisplay(CO2_Window,main='Monthly Carbon Dioxide Levels')

There is trend, the ACF does not die down - not stationary

Is variance not constant with level?

lambda_rec<-BoxCox.lambda(CO2_Window)
lambda_rec
## [1] 1.072681

Not a strong transformation

CO2_Window_trf<-BoxCox(CO2_Window,lambda=lambda_rec)
plot(CO2_Window_trf,ylab='Emission Transformed')

kpss - null hypothesis is stationary, alternative is non-stationary

kpss.test(CO2_Window_trf)
## Warning in kpss.test(CO2_Window_trf): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  CO2_Window_trf
## KPSS Level = 2.0101, Truncation lag parameter = 4, p-value = 0.01

p value of .01<.05 –>non-stationary

CO2_Window_diff1<-diff(CO2_Window_trf,lag=12)
plot(CO2_Window_diff1)

kpss.test(CO2_Window_diff1)
## Warning in kpss.test(CO2_Window_diff1): p-value greater than printed p-value
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  CO2_Window_diff1
## KPSS Level = 0.058326, Truncation lag parameter = 4, p-value = 0.1

p-value > .05 means series is stationary

Seasonal differece of 1 gets to stationary

Do my own SARIMA modeling & then compare to auto.arima()

acf(CO2_Window_diff1)

Sinusoidal decay implies AR() process

pacf(CO2_Window_diff1)

mod_func_RAR <- function(y, h, xreg)
{
  X <- xreg[1:length(y),]
  if(NROW(xreg) < length(y) + h)
    stop("Not enough xreg data for forecasting")
  newX <- xreg[length(y)+(1:h),]
  fit <- auto.arima(y, xreg=X,D=1,lambda=0)
  forecast(fit, xreg=newX)
}

Regression with Arima Errors

consumption_final<-window(electric_consumption,start=2008)
consumption_train<-window(consumption_final,end=2018)
consumption_test<-window(CO2_Window,start=2018)
Consum_finalaarima_1<-auto.arima(consumption_train)
Consum_finalaarima_1
